message.content:
The command you provided is a Secure Shell (SSH) command that establishes a secure, encrypted connection to a remote server hosted on Amazon Web Services (AWS). Here's a breakdown of the components:

1. `ssh`: The SSH command is used for executing commands and transferring files between a local machine and a remote machine securely.
2. `-i "~/UserKey.pem"`: This flag specifies the path to an identity file (in this case, UserKey.pem) that contains the public key for authentication with the remote server. The `~` symbol represents the home directory of the user executing the command.
3. `-C`: This flag enables compression on the connection, which can improve performance and reduce data transfer times.
4. `-L 25900:localhost:5900`: This flag sets up a local port forwarding. It forwards connections to the specified local port (25900 in this case) to the remote server on the specified remote port (5900 in this case). The `localhost` indicates that the connection should be forwarded to the same machine running the SSH command.
5. `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com`: This is the remote server's address, consisting of the username (user), the public DNS hostname of an EC2 instance in the US West (N. California) region provided by AWS (ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com).

To summarize, this command establishes a secure SSH connection with port forwarding to access a remote server hosted on AWS, allowing you to connect to the specified local port (25900) on your local machine and have it forwarded to the remote server's port 5900.
